Subject: Rate-limited event-driven capture in display_evdi_t

Replaces the original display_evdi_t::capture fixed-delay sleep loop
with a hybrid:

  - HARD rate cap via `next_frame = last_frame_time + delay` (same
    as the original loop) — never capture faster than the configured
    fps. Without this cap, the previous attempt at this patch let
    capture run at whatever rate kwin pageflipped to the EVDI card.
    If a game asked for >60Hz the loop captured at that rate, overran
    the encoder, network dropped frames, and the user saw 47-50fps
    + visible tearing despite vsync.
  - EARLY-WAKE via condition-variable wait: between captures we sleep
    on `buffer_->wait_for_update(last_fn, remaining_budget)` instead
    of `std::this_thread::sleep_for(...)`. The libevdi event pump
    notifies the condvar in mark_updated() after grab_pixels, so we
    wake immediately when a fresh frame is available, eliminating the
    0-16ms phase-jitter of fixed-delay polling.

EvdiBuffer gains:
  - std::condition_variable cond_  (notified by mark_updated)
  - uint64_t wait_for_update(last_fn, timeout) — atomically blocks
    until frame_number > last_fn or timeout, returns current frame_number

mark_updated() now calls cond_.notify_all() after the atomic increment.

Result: capture rate is exactly the configured fps (60Hz), each
capture sees the freshest available frame, and we never overrun the
encoder. No more wakeup-then-stale-buffer or wakeup-then-late patterns.

Combined with patch 0009 (exact 60Hz EDID) and patches 0013/0014
(AMD VBR rate control + low-latency encoder options), the stream
should hold a stable 60fps.

Note: the original "PBO async CPU→GPU upload" attempt (was patch 0017)
turned out to add a one-frame latency penalty on AMD UMA hardware
that outweighed any throughput benefit (shared memory means the
synchronous TexSubImage2D is already near-zero cost). That patch
was archived; we kept the simple synchronous upload.

--- a/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.h
+++ b/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.h
@@ -6,6 +6,8 @@
 
 // standard includes
 #include <atomic>
+#include <chrono>
+#include <condition_variable>
 #include <cstdint>
 #include <functional>
 #include <memory>
@@ -207,8 +209,24 @@
     /// Called by the libevdi event pump after a successful grab_pixels.
     void mark_updated();
 
+    /**
+     * @brief Block until the buffer has been updated past `last_frame_number`,
+     * or until `timeout` elapses.
+     *
+     * Used by display_evdi_t::capture (kmsgrab.cpp) to wake immediately
+     * when libevdi's event pump produces a fresh frame, instead of
+     * sleeping a fixed delay and possibly catching a stale buffer.
+     * Combined with a wall-clock rate limit in the caller, this gives
+     * jitter-free 60fps capture (no over-rate, no under-rate).
+     *
+     * @return the new frame_number (>= last_frame_number+1) on update,
+     *         or last_frame_number if the wait timed out.
+     */
+    uint64_t wait_for_update(uint64_t last_frame_number, std::chrono::milliseconds timeout);
+
    private:
     mutable std::mutex mutex_;
+    mutable std::condition_variable cond_;  // notified by mark_updated()
     std::vector<uint8_t> data_;
     uint32_t width_;
     uint32_t height_;
--- a/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
+++ b/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
@@ -263,6 +263,16 @@
 
   void EvdiBuffer::mark_updated() {
     frame_number_.fetch_add(1, std::memory_order_release);
+    cond_.notify_all();
+  }
+
+  uint64_t EvdiBuffer::wait_for_update(uint64_t last_frame_number,
+                                       std::chrono::milliseconds timeout) {
+    std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lock(mutex_);
+    cond_.wait_for(lock, timeout, [&] {
+      return frame_number_.load(std::memory_order_acquire) > last_frame_number;
+    });
+    return frame_number_.load(std::memory_order_acquire);
   }
 
   // libevdi global event-pump thread state. See evdi_events_loop().
